# PUF-Based Edge Device Attestation System
### Rutgers Hardware & System Security — Rahul Biju — Spring 2026

---

## Project Overview

This project implements a Physical Unclonable Function (PUF) based device
attestation system. A Zybo Z7 FPGA acts as the Prover (generates a unique
hardware fingerprint), a Raspberry Pi 3 acts as the Verifier (enrolls and
authenticates the device), and a PC-hosted HIL simulation allows full
protocol testing without hardware.

---

## File Structure

```
~/puf_project/
│
├── virtual_puf.py          # Virtual RO-PUF model (silicon + noise simulation)
├── hil_simulation.py       # Full HIL simulation runner
├── hil_uart_bridge.py      # TCP socket bridge (makes virtual PUF speak Zybo protocol)
├── pi_verifier.py          # Raspberry Pi verifier (enrollment + authentication)
├── plot_results.py         # Plot generator from CSV logs
│
├── hil_output/             # Created automatically on first run
│   ├── auth_log.csv
│   ├── noise_sweep_log.csv
│   ├── intra_hd_log.csv
│   ├── inter_hd_log.csv
│   └── plots/
│       ├── 1_auth_log.png
│       ├── 2_noise_sweep.png
│       ├── 3_intra_hd.png
│       └── 4_inter_hd.png
│
└── verifier_output/        # Created automatically on first run
    ├── crps.json           # Golden challenge-response pairs
    ├── pi_auth_log.csv
    └── pi_stress_summary.csv
```

---

## Dependencies

Install on both PC (WSL/Ubuntu) and Raspberry Pi:

```bash
pip install numpy matplotlib pandas pyserial --break-system-packages
```

---

## Option A — HIL Simulation (no hardware needed)

Run everything on your PC. No Zybo or Pi required.

### Step 1 — Basic simulation (enrollment + auth + stress + Trojan + metrics)

```bash
cd ~/puf_project
python3 hil_simulation.py
```

**What it does:**
- Enrolls 64 challenges against the virtual PUF
- Runs normal authentication
- Runs 20-trial stress test
- Enables Trojan mode and shows BER spike
- Computes intra-device and inter-device Hamming Distance
- Saves all results to ./hil_output/

**Expected output:**
```
[Verifier] Enrollment complete — 64 CRPs stored.
[Normal]  Match Rate: 98.4%  BER: 1.56%  ✅ PASS
Pass rate: 20/20  Avg BER: 7.2%
[Trojan]  Match Rate: 79.7%  BER: 20.3%  ❌ FAIL  ⚠️ TROJAN DETECTED
```

---

### Step 2 — Noise sweep (BER characterization)

```bash
python3 hil_simulation.py --sweep
```

Sweeps noise from 0% to 1.5% and logs BER vs noise level.
Required before running plot_results.py (generates noise_sweep_log.csv).

---

### Step 3 — Generate plots

```bash
python3 plot_results.py
```

Generates 4 PNG plots in ./hil_output/plots/:
- 1_auth_log.png      — match rate and BER per run
- 2_noise_sweep.png   — BER vs noise level (normal vs Trojan)
- 3_intra_hd.png      — intra-device Hamming Distance (reliability)
- 4_inter_hd.png      — inter-device Hamming Distance (uniqueness)

Copy plots to Windows Desktop from WSL:
```bash
cp ~/puf_project/hil_output/plots/*.png /mnt/c/Users/Rahul/Desktop/
```

---

### Step 4 — HIL bridge + Pi verifier on same PC (two terminals)

Simulates the Pi talking to the virtual Zybo over a local TCP socket.

**Terminal 1 — start the bridge (virtual Zybo):**
```bash
cd ~/puf_project
python3 hil_uart_bridge.py
```

**Terminal 2 — run the verifier:**
```bash
cd ~/puf_project
python3 pi_verifier.py --hil
```

**With Trojan mode on:**
```bash
python3 hil_uart_bridge.py --trojan
python3 pi_verifier.py --hil
```

**With custom noise:**
```bash
python3 hil_uart_bridge.py --noise 0.3
```

---

## Option B — Real Hardware (Zybo + Raspberry Pi)

### Requirements
- Zybo Z7 programmed with puf_top.bit via Vivado Hardware Manager
- PmodUSBUART plugged into Zybo JB header
- USB cable from PmodUSBUART to Raspberry Pi
- Pi connected to same WiFi as your laptop (for SSH)

### Step 1 — SSH into the Pi

```bash
ssh pi@raspberrypi.local
# or by IP:
ssh pi@10.16.196.37
# password: raspberry
```

### Step 2 — Confirm Zybo is detected

```bash
ls /dev/ttyUSB*
# Should show: /dev/ttyUSB0
```

### Step 3 — Basic enrollment and authentication

```bash
cd ~/puf_project
python3 pi_verifier.py --port /dev/ttyUSB0
```

**Expected output:**
```
[UART] Connected to /dev/ttyUSB0 @ 115200 baud
[Verifier] Enrollment Phase
  Progress: 16/64 challenges collected
  Progress: 32/64 challenges collected
  Progress: 48/64 challenges collected
  Progress: 64/64 challenges collected
  Done. 1s: 12  0s: 52  (ideal ~50/50)
[CRPStore] Saved to verifier_output/crps.json

[Verifier] Authentication (normal)
  Match: 100.0%  BER: 0.00%  ✅ PASS
```

### Step 4 — Stress test (20 trials)

```bash
python3 pi_verifier.py --port /dev/ttyUSB0 --stress 20 --load-crps verifier_output/crps.json
```

Skips re-enrollment by loading saved CRPs, then runs 20 auth trials.

### Step 5 — Trojan demonstration

**Terminal 1 on Pi — inject Trojan:**
```bash
python3 -c "
import serial, time
s = serial.Serial('/dev/ttyUSB0', 115200, timeout=3)
s.write(b'TROJAN:ON\n')
print(s.readline())
"
```

**Terminal 2 on Pi — run authentication:**
```bash
python3 pi_verifier.py --port /dev/ttyUSB0 --load-crps verifier_output/crps.json
```

Watch LED1 on the Zybo turn ON when Trojan is active.
Match rate should drop and verifier flags anomaly.

**Turn Trojan off:**
```bash
python3 -c "
import serial
s = serial.Serial('/dev/ttyUSB0', 115200, timeout=3)
s.write(b'TROJAN:OFF\n')
print(s.readline())
"
```

### Step 6 — Copy results back to laptop

Run this from WSL on your laptop (not on the Pi):
```bash
scp pi@10.16.196.37:~/puf_project/verifier_output/*.csv ~/puf_project/hil_output/
```

Then generate plots:
```bash
cd ~/puf_project
python3 plot_results.py
```

---

## Command Reference

### hil_simulation.py

| Flag | Description | Default |
|---|---|---|
| (none) | Run full simulation | — |
| --sweep | Run noise sweep 0–1.5% | — |
| --noise 0.3 | Set noise level | 0.1 |

### hil_uart_bridge.py

| Flag | Description | Default |
|---|---|---|
| --port 9999 | TCP port | 9999 |
| --noise 0.2 | Noise level | 0.1 |
| --trojan | Start with Trojan ON | off |
| --challenges 64 | Number of challenges | 64 |

### pi_verifier.py

| Flag | Description | Default |
|---|---|---|
| --port /dev/ttyUSB0 | Force UART port | auto-detect |
| --hil | Force HIL socket mode | auto-detect |
| --hil-host localhost | HIL bridge host | localhost |
| --hil-port 9999 | HIL bridge port | 9999 |
| --challenges 64 | Number of challenges | 64 |
| --vote 9 | Majority vote N | 9 |
| --threshold 0.90 | Auth pass threshold | 0.90 |
| --stress 20 | Run N stress trials | 0 |
| --load-crps path | Load existing CRPs | (re-enroll) |
| --save-crps path | Where to save CRPs | verifier_output/crps.json |

---

## Troubleshooting

**"No Prover found" error**
- Check USB cable is connected from PmodUSBUART to Pi
- Run `ls /dev/ttyUSB*` to confirm /dev/ttyUSB0 exists
- Confirm Zybo is powered and bitstream is loaded (DONE LED green)
- Press BTN0 on Zybo to reset if FSM is stuck

**"pyserial not installed"**
```bash
pip install pyserial --break-system-packages
```

**SCP can't find Pi by hostname**
Use IP address instead:
```bash
scp pi@10.16.196.37:~/puf_project/verifier_output/*.csv ~/puf_project/hil_output/
```

**plot_results.py says noise_sweep_log.csv not found**
Run the sweep first:
```bash
python3 hil_simulation.py --sweep
```

**Pi SSH "remote host identification changed"**
```bash
ssh-keygen -R raspberrypi.local
ssh pi@raspberrypi.local
```

**Vivado can't find Zybo**
- Check USB cable to PROG/UART port (not USB OTG)
- Flow → Open Hardware Manager → Auto Connect
- If still not found, reinstall Digilent drivers

---

## LED Guide (Zybo Z7)

| LED | Pin | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| LED0 | M14 | Last CHAL response bit (flickers during enrollment) |
| LED1 | M15 | Trojan mode active (ON = fault injected) |
| DONE | — | Bitstream loaded successfully |
| PGOOD | — | Board powered |

